Packing supplies for genetic engineering kits

If we weren't the ones who invented these kits I couldn't imagine a cooler Christmas gift than learning to engineer life. To me genetic engineering is so much more than just changing DNA though. It's investing in being a steward of our societies genetic future and building that future. But it's ok to just do it for fun. We have kits for $39.99 that let you put a jellyfish gene in microorganisms to make them glow. A kit for $169 that allows you to draw on plant leaves using genetic alterations. Engineer brewing yeast or human cells all in your kitchen with no experience required. Sometimes even I'm surprised it's actually real. Srsly, check out our shit. I can't imagine someone would be disappointed with it as a gift.

I left a bag of decomposing pig's feet in my backyard and they were gone by the morning. 😅

I've been experimenting with preserving big pieces of wet tissue in as near to natural form as possible for storage at room temperature outside of a jar. Weird art project idea. Don't ask? I simultaneously am very intrigued and very repulsed by the feel of a liver and other tissue. The problem is you are constantly fighting against death, bacteria and oxygen. It's a wonder how our tissues last. Immune systems, pumping blood and living cells. The slow color change to blue greenish is really interesting. It is what I assume is iron oxidation? Sorry if it grosses you out.

The Time Keeper
Human rib bones, Fomes fomentarius mushroom, clay, thread, river rocks

By @jzayner & @lera.niemackl 

A clay piece reminiscent of an insect carapace is precariously balanced atop human rib bones. Smooth river rocks are wrapped just enough in thread to provide the ability to hang on. They are drapped over the top creating a delicate balance between instability and functionality. A controlled chaos. As the mushroom material burns at a rate of about 10 minutes an inch it leaves a musty incense like smell in the air. Eventually the thread burns and rocks drop making loud noises signifying a passage of time. 

This piece represents the inevitable passage of life and time and our connection to nature. How even in the most primitive context time still passes and death still chases us even when we aren't paying attention to it. Life and biology is a kind of controlled chaos.

We kind of had a running joke that this piece wouldn't survive the art show. It broke a few times while setting it up but we incorporated the broken pieces as part of the work. It did survive though and worked as planned. Which was really cool.

#art #artwork

Today is Trans day of Visibility. This is my body as a transwoman. It's who I am. I never wanted to post about trans awareness. I have enough shit from governments and regulators to deal with in my life. And people just want me to post about Biohacking. Here's the thing, every trans person is a biohacker. They take hormones and drugs and have procedures done and their body changes. They are more of a biohacker than most people will ever be. I've grown breasts and a butt and more. My body has changed completely. I get to be that person I always saw myself as. It's pretty amazing. I never imagined I could be this happy with who I was. And it's bigger than being trans, it's body autonomy. I want everyone to have the bodily attributes that they want. Coming out and living my life as trans has been one of the hardest but best things of my life. I hope it inspires people to be who they want to be.

Literally, my only regret in life, and I've done a lot of questionable things, is my regret of not coming out sooner and getting care sooner. Even though everyday I'm afraid to interact with the world. I'm afraid of hate and bigots, using public bathrooms and looking silly. Even though I open up social media every day and see trans hate coded in propaganda that is creating laws against me for just being me. It's impossible that someone should feel that they need to defend their right to exist every day. But I do and I would do it again. Because I look cute as f$*& 

Denying people gender affirming care is denying people medical care, period. That medical care reduces their risk of suicide by over 70%. It's denying people happiness and acceptance of who they are. If we could give people a drug in any other context that would do those things it would happen so fast. People who support anti-trans legislation need to stop pretending they are trying to protect people and save lives when the solution to save the lives of trans youth and adults is just to provide the medical care they need and deserve. 

It also helps people grow boobs and who is against more boobs in the world? amirite?

I remember when I first started trying to work with human cells outside of the sterile lab environment I had experienced at @uchicago
and @nasa . Everybody told me it was impossible. I'm almost believed them. I killed lots of cells in that first year. But I didn't give up and finally I could gene mod human cells without fancy equipment in my kitchen. I'ma be honest, one of the things I am most proud of is the work we have done to make accessible growing and gene moding human and animals cells. 

What can you do with this tech? Grow stem cells from your own body. Test gene therapies. Create disease models. We have done all these things and more!

Still waiting for the world to catch up to us with this tech and see wider adoption and use.

Not Long for this World Art Show

There was an apocalyptic event and I was one of the survivors, the other, my lover. We were living alone together in a safe house surviving the apocalypse when my lover passed away. In deep pain and mourning I started to build devices using her organs that contributed to my survival, helped me keep going while living trapped alone in this space. 

Her brain
This piece was a real brain connected to an old TV that played memories from the life of my recently deceased lover. 

I'm really into retro-futuristic aesthetics. This to me also really brings out a hacker aesthetic because interfacing the modern world or modern ideas with old things can look very messy, kludgey, hackery. One of my goals in art is to remove this separation of reality and imagination. To make people question what is real and what is possible. I tried to push that in this show by using real unpreserved organs in almost all the pieces. Sourcing and being able to keep fresh a real brain of human proportions was a task in itself.

I think reality breaking works is a genre of art that we are starting to see more of, exemplified by works of @agnesquestionmark @nadialeecohen @patricia.piccinini and others

Lots of technical work went into this piece. Connecting an old TV to modern hardware. The static on the TV is actually generated from a program I wrote in Python that uses brain wave data I recorded from my brain's frontal lobe while I was imagining the emotional turmoil from my fictional lovers death. A beautifully handcrafted TV stand 😅 I kid, but the stand actually turned out better than I imagined it in my head.

There was an apocalyptic event and I was one of the survivors, the other, my lover. We were living alone together in a safe house surviving the apocalypse when my lover passed away. In deep pain and mourning I started to build devices using her organs that contributed to my survival, helped me keep going while living trapped alone in this space. 

Her Heart
A beating heart powers a flickering unplugged lamp on the bedside table. Occasionally, the heart stops beating and the light goes out when it does.

I don't think it is reasonable for a heart to power a lamp but I also don't think it is unreasonable. This piece leaned a little more into surrealism and how we view a heart as this life and energy force. I enjoy magical realism and have often been inspired by the writings of Haruki Murakami. 

Originally, I wanted to "power" all the electricity in the show from this heart but this being an amazing piece I wanted people to be drawn to the flickering light in the corner.

This was one of the first pieces I started working on, maybe like a year ago. An inspiration to everything else. The beating of the heart is caused by a motor inside it. The lamp was a thrift store find that I spent an afternoon "weathering" the metal with acids and salts. A programmed microcontroller controls the beating and the light. All electronics, programming and organ preservation done by me. The heart is stitched on one side using wool thread hand spun by @k.oxier.mori and the animal hides used to hide all sorts of electronics trickery are also from her. 

Somehow the piece wasn't working about 4 hours before the show and I tried frantically to test everything. After an hour I found some programming error. The error didn't make any sense because I had always been using the same code even when it worked just fine. I ended up getting it working just in time.

A piece from the Not Long for this World Art Show at Tyrell Gallery @tyrellgallery
The premise of the show was an apocalyptic event and I was one of the survivors, the other, my lover. We were living alone together in a safe house surviving the apocalypse when my lover passed away. In deep pain and mourning I started to build devices using her organs that contributed to my survival, helped me keep going while living trapped alone in this space. 

Her Lungs
Real Lungs connected to a vintage gas mask that inflate and deflate with the users breathing. Used in the performance as an air filtering breathing apparatus when Josie finally decides to venture off into the world.

This was such an amazing piece. I was amazed at the structure and toughness that lungs had. I was also amazed at just how much they changed when they were inflated vs flaccid. I really can't believe this piece came together and worked out exactly as I had envisioned it. The gas mask needed to be modified slightly to allow proper breathing. The lungs were preserved in 20% alcohol at around 2C. You definitely got alcohol fumes when breathing in and out in them. I really can't believe this piece worked out as well as it did. One of my faves for sure.
